<head>
<title>Why did AFL-CIO chief George Meany help Warren Carroll...</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" 
align="left" ISMAP></a>
<center><h2>Culture Watch</h2></center>
<BR>
<center><h2>Why Did America's First Woman Televsion sportscaster become a
conservative radio talk-show hostess?</h2><BR>
</center>
<center><h3>by Laurence Jarvik</h3></center>
<blockquote>
<P>
<DD><FONT SIZE=+2><I>J</I></FONT>ane Chastain lives about as far as it is possible to be from
Washington, DC's notorious Beltway. Her home sits atop a mountain
outside Palm Springs, California. She commutes to her apperances
on CNN and Crawford broadcasting's radio shows in her Cessna 336
from the landing strip in front of her home (both she and her
husband, Roger Chastain, are licensed pilots with multiand instrument
ratings). Chastain is a frequent guest on &quot;CNN and Company&quot;
and author of <I>I'd Speak Out On The Issues If I Only Knew What
To Say</I> (Regal Books, 1987). She contributed a chapter to <I>Good
Will Toward Men</I> (St. Martin's Press, 1994), a book in praise of
the masculine sex and has her own newsletter called <I>On The Issues</I>.
Her Crawford Broadcasting radio talk show, &quot;What Washington
Doesn't Want You To Know,&quot; is syndicated to l8 stations from
Southern California's KBRT. Chastain was one of the first &quot;Renaissance&quot;
women to join the prestigious Washington leadership group founded
by Ambassador Holland Coors and Nina May in 1983, which has grown
to 6,000 members.
<P>
Chastain began her career as &quot;Coach Friday&quot; on Atlanta's WAGA in 1963,
 eventually moving to Miami's WTVJ, where for 9 years she worked as a sports reporter. 
She syndicated a radio series called <I>Football for Women</I>--ironically designed to
explain the sport to her husband, a race car driver and designer
who didn't understand the principles of the game--followed by
another series of 260 shows called Girls Rules, syndicated to
205 radio stations. This led to a television deal: 195 90--second
spots syndicated to 88 television stations called <I>The Jane Chastain
Show: Evertyhing You've Always Wanted To Know About Sports But
Were Afraid To Ask.</I> Still in her twenties, Jane Chastain was a
television star. In 1974 CBS hired her as the first woman network
sportscaster in the country. She covered NBA basketball, the Pan
American Games, pro golf, tennis, cycling, and surfing. She was
a pit reporter for auto racing coverage. Most importantly, Chastain
covered NFL football, including the Sun Bowl and the Cotton Bowl,
and developed stong ties to the Miami Dolphins and their winning
coach, Don Shula.
<P>
<BR>
When Chastain first came to Dolphin coach George Wilson,  however, he objected 
to the idea of a woman sportscaster. &quot;Well, she won't come to my
camp, &quot; Wilson vowed. Chastain patiently persevered, attended
training camp, and by the end of the season Wilson had responded
to her determination. He came up to her and announced, &quot;I'll
give you that interview.&quot; After the session, she recalled,
&quot;the players ran over, picked me up, and threw me in the
Dumpster. And it was like saying, 'Okay, you've made it; you've
been accepted; you're one of us. Congratulations.'&quot; Unlike
some feminists who might have filed a harrassment complaint these
days, Chastain took her experience as a compliment. She later
told an interviewer, &quot;Well, I think it was a friendly gesture.
I hadn't tried to make an issue of what Wilson was doing. I never
went up to those players and bellyached and complained about their
boss; I never put them in a compromising position of having to
talk to me about what an awful person Coach Wilson was. I think
the fact that I didn't make an issue out if it is actually what
caused him to address it. If you have a disagreement with somebody
and you try to back them up against the wall, then they get caught
up in defending themselves rather than examining their own position
to see if it's tenable.&quot;  Chastain has overcome personal
obstacles as well. When an Atlanta station executive started giving
her a hard time, after confessing he was in love with her and
finding himself rejected, Chastain went looking for another job.
She got an interview at a Raleigh, North Carolina television station
and was hired by Jesse Helms -- over vocal objections from the
station's executive vice-president, who didn't believe women should
cover sports.  &quot;It makes the hair on the back of my neck
stand up when I hear accusations that Jesse's against women,&quot;
Chastain says. &quot;I expected my career was over, and he gave
me a chance. He did more for hiring women and people of color
than anyone I knew in broadcasting.&quot; 
<P>
<BR>
Locker rooms held no charm for Chastain at first, and she tried to avoid entering the male  
domain while working at local stations. &quot;I didn't think
they should have to give interviews in various stages of undress,&quot;
she says. But when she became the first woman sportscaster for
CBS in 1974, Chastain was required to go inside to conduct interviews
in order to meet -- and beat -- her competitors.  The invasion
of privacy still rankles her. &quot;You will not find any men
demanding access to the female's dressing rooms. They have not
allowed male reporters in there. Yet, on the other side, in the
male locker room, everyone is afraid to say no.&quot; Chastain
dealt with the challenge as discreetly as possible, setting up
her cameras facing a wall by the door so that she would not be
exposed to the athletes against their will, and arranging to leave
the locker room as soon as the interviews had been completed.
&quot;Now, that didn't mean I was a prude,&quot; she recalled.
&quot;I'd been married for a number of years and didn't expect
to see anything that I hadn't seen before. I just respected their
privacy.&quot; But her personal experience with the double standard
helped plant a seed of doubt about the claims of the feminist
movement.  Eventually, America's first female sportscaster would
become a devoted opponent of the goals and tactics of the women's
liberation movement.
<P>
<BR>
Motherhood made all the difference for Jane 
   Chastain. She realized her viewpoint was 
       no longer that of a careerist in 1975 while covering the
Pan American Games for CBS. &quot;When I called home every night
and heard my baby cry, that's when my own priorities changed,&quot;
she recalled.&quot; And it didn't take long for me to discover
that the quality of time I was able to give my family was actually
in an inverse ratio to the quantity of time I spent on my job.&quot;
In 1976 she became sports anchor at KABC in Los Angeles, and in
1978 struck out on her own as a documentary filmmaker, author,
and radio personality on both National Public Radio and the Sports
Radio Network. Yet in her work, Chastain decided to confront feminism
directly, pointing out that sixty-one percent of the nation's
top female executives are childless, as opposed to fourteen percent
of the women in the general population.&quot;I talked about the
fact that female physicians take fewer patients per hour, and
choose to work fewer hours,&quot; she says. &quot;You don't get
to the top job on flextime.&quot; Chastain said she realized that
feminists &quot;don't play fair, they want their piece of cake
and yours, too.&quot; Soon Chastain was in the public eye as a
vocal opponent of the movement. She testified to the Presidential
Commission on Women in Combat against sending women into battle,
in her newsletter she published the findings of the Center for
Military Readiness on double standards applied to female aviators,
and she wrote columns arguing that the feminists were prepared
to sacrifice the lives of American women to promote their ideology.
&quot;Is it fair that we ask these same women to go into combat
against the all-male armies of countries that are not equal opportunity
employers?&quot; she asked. &quot;Our women will be putting out
an equal effort, but in the end they will be dying in unequal
numbers.&quot; 
<P>
<BR>
<I>[Jane Chastain can be reached at On The Issues, P.O. Box 2122,
Garden Grove, CA 92642-2122, (714)754-4450]<BR>
<BR>
</I>
