and CPSC Vice Chairman Mary Gall
</ul>
<P>
<a name="summ"></a>

<h3>Executive Summary</h3>
<i>The Rise of the Nanny
State</i> examines the origins, goals, and activities of the modern
consumer movement--a movement that, in the words of Capital Research
Center Visiting Fellow Tom Holt, &quot;does not address the needs
of consumers.  
<P>
Instead, it serves the bureaucratic interests of
governing elites and the ideological and organizational interests
of the movement itself.&quot; Holt paints a decidedly unflattering
portrait of the consumer movement.  As the recent Alar scare showed,
consumer advocates capitalize on the public's ignorance of science
and the media's eagerness for calamity.  Under the guise of public
health and safety, they seek to justify regulations dictating
their idea of the public good to our households and workplaces.
<P>
 With few exceptions, they advocate bigger and more intrusive
government and are hostile to free markets and personal responsibility.
Holt shows that the consumer movement has imposed significant
costs on industry--costs ultimately passed on to consumers--and
has violated individual freedoms in a futile effort to protect
us from our own actions and judgment.  Based on his analysis,
he calls for: major tort reform; the abolition of CAFE standards
and the Delaney clause; a reduced federal role in health care;
a major overhaul of the Consumer Product Safety Commission; and
other reforms of regulatory agencies.
</ul>
</blockquote>
