<TITLE>NR Soapbox-weekday</TITLE>


<CENTER><img src="/nationalreview/images/soap2.gif" ALT="NR Soapbox"></center>.

<P>
<!---------------------------------------------------------------->
<blockquote>

The NR Soapbox is a place where <I>NR Online</I> readers can voice their opinions regarding the major issues of the day. Respond to the question directly, or comment on previous responses. Please keep comments brief (100 words or fewer). The featured question will change at the end of each week; comments will be updated daily.</blockquote>
<P>
<center>This week's question is:</center>
<center><H1><I>Should Congress Put A Rein on the Courts?</I></H1></center>


<br>
<center>To submit your comments,</center><br>
<center><A HREF="mailto:nronline@ix.netcom.com"><img src="/nationalreview/images/click2.gif" ALT="Click Here"></a>.<br></center>
<P>
Updated  1/6/97 (Well, not quite. See below.)
<HR>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<P>
<b>AN APOLOGY: We are having problems gaining access to responses to this week's Soapbox question. We have just moved our offices, and are in the process of dealing with numerous communications snafus. We <I>will</I> post your submissions just as soon as our local phone company figures out how to fix our problems. Please continue to check in with us on daily basis, as we may have a handle on this as early as tommorrow (<I>HA!</I>). Please bear with us as we try to straighten this out. Thank you for being patient.</b>
<P>

<hr>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------>
1/2/97<br>
Congress overseeing the courts!This might be the most frightening thought I've ever had. The Constitution provides for Judicial Review whereby the Supreme Court determines the constitutionality of law. The courts were established to de-politicize the law. We are now considering turning this on its head? Would Dick Gephardt find that <I>Roe</I> v. <I>Wade</I> was a clear instance of the Court making law rather than interpreting it? Would Newt Gingrich find that 209 is unconstitutional (a point with which I disagree)? No . . . they are partisan. Congress was given the power to confirm or reject any nominee. Perhaps if they took that responsibility more seriously, most questions of the court's integrity would simply disappear.<br>
<I>breiferson@bloomaddept.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes, Congress should make laws that regulate the courts, but not in a way that compromises the separation of powers, and certainly not based on politics or public opinion. Rather, the law should mandate that the Bench include a significant number of non-attorneys. There is utterly no reason that lawyers should run all three branches of government, in addition to business, politics and especially legal education.<br>
<I>j chanse, law student</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Yes. It's still "We the people . . ."; not, "I the judge . . ."<br>
<I>Martin Registrada, Beaumont, Texas, registrada@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>

Yes, congress should have the power to override a court decision. The Supreme Court is the most powerful branch in our government. Congress should exercise their rights using the elastic clause. Congress should be able to overturn ludicrous decisions that undermine the values of America. Decisions in cases such as Roe vs. Wade and those taking the Ten Commandments and prayer out of schools should be reviewed by Congress and if found necessary "veto" the Court's decision.<br>
<I>Andrew C.Pearson Jr.</I>

<hr>
<P>
1/2/97<br>
Given the philosophy of your motley crew, I suggest you skip this step to curb the power of our courts, which have apparently functioned fairly well for over two hundred years, and just do away with them altogether. Then I would put Strom Thurmond in the White House so we could wave the Klan flag over the White House.<br>
<I>Mario H. de la Plata, delaplat@ix.netcom.com</I>
