<P>

12/18/96<br>
Randy and others, It should be clear to you since the election that leaving pure politics in the hands of the electorate is a lost cause. Instant gratification is the rule of the land in their minds. Americans in general have their wants, their needs, and their rights muddled together. They think that if they want something bad enough it becomes a need. And if they can't get it, it becomes their right to have it. It seems the judiciary feeds on this and therefore the legislature is so busy trying to "fix" what the courts decree that they are unable to make reasonable law.<br> 
<I>dmartin@vbe.com</I> 
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
This is an easy one. The courts are NOT allowed to hear cases involving the internal affairs of any state. Article III, Section 2, not to mention Amendment X of the US Constitution, spell out the scope of Judicial power. The courts may not hear cases involving the laws of a particular state, unless it is appealed as to an issue arising under the US Constitution. Most of the cases heard by the Court do not fall under its legal scope, and are therefore null and void. California Prop 187, 209, <I>Roe</I> v <I>Wade</I>, etc. are internal state affairs and out of the reach of the federal courts. Judges and Justices who do not respect their very limited scope should be removed for behavior inconsistent with their service. The US Constitution is a very precise and clear document; there are no "vapors," "emanations", or "penumbras" incorporated into its substance. Justices who have a difficult time with this concept should be promptly retired.<br>  
<I>alohawz@aloha.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

What Congress should do is actively review the decisions of courts such as the decision which occurred in California to block the popular implementation of Prop. 209 to end affirmative action. Congressional committees should be formed to look into controversial exercise of judicial power and decide if the federal judges making such decisions by their records merit impeachment. The indefinite terms of federal judges were meant to shield them from the influence of short-term political pressures, but liberal judges have regarded them as means to thwart the implementation of conservative legislation. Congress should simply exercise their powers to protect the rights of citizens in the practice of democracy.<br>  
<I>Dan Shaw, dshaw@nbserv2.dseg.ti.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
The real question is: Who runs this country? The people or an elite bunch of self-serving educrats who know what is best for each of us? Someday the people of this country might stand up for what is right!<br>  
<I>Eric P. Thompson, ept51@ctainforms.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

The Congress should put a rein on the courts, but it won't. As long as the Supreme Court keeps giving liberals the decisions they want, Democrats will block any efforts to restore power to the legislatures. Almost all the checks and balances on the courts require either two-thirds of Congress, or 60% of the Senate and presidential signature, neither of which Republicans are likely to have anytime soon. Senate Republicans could block Clinton's liberal appointments, but they are too gutless. Court reform is just not going to happen.<br>  
<I>Russell Van Zandt, russvz@wwa.com</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

If you think that control over the judicial system should be given to Congress, now that Congress is in conservative hands, remember what happened to Robert Bork when he sought confirmation. Remember what almost happened to Clarence Thomas. However, judges and the activist legislation they create must be brought under control, since they are now essentially unaccountable. There have been no checks on judges' activist liberalism, which is why we're in the trouble we're in today; the people themselves never voted for most of the liberal legislation that is destroying this country. However, the power to make judges accountable must not lie with Congress, since Congress itself was unaccountable for 40 years of nonstop liberal Democrat rule. There should be a safeguard within the system itself, a safeguard that is regulated by the Constitution. The only real safeguard would be a Constitutional amendment that Congress cannot touch, an amendment limiting the power of judges. This could take the form of term limits, recall, or legislation that requires strict construction of the Constitution in any judicial interpretation. Newt Gingrich often states that the Founding Fathers designed a system so inefficient that no dictator could force it to work. But unfortunately, it wasn't so inefficient that Congressional barons, imperial presidents, and judicial petty tyrants couldn't find loopholes. All of these branches, rather than acting as checks and balances on each other, have conspired to create dictatorial agencies that go unregulated, and legislation that is beyond the reach of the public. The key to getting this leviathan state under control is not to give any one branch special jurisdiction over anothersuch as Congressional control over the judiciarybut to put the entire system in a strait jacket. We must tie the entire system in so many knots that it will have to become responsive to the people that it is supposed to serve. This might take the form of limiting executive privilege and autonomy, enacting term limits on Congress, giving Congress control over Federal agencies, enacting a balanced budget amendment, and so on. The government should have unlimited authority to control itself while leaving us free. However, this may well be impossible, since the ability to tie the system in knots implies the existence of a degree of control that we no longer have, if we ever really had it at all. Ultimately, the ability to control the system lies with the peopleand if the people remain ignorant, shallow, emotion-driven, dull-witted, and foolish in their condition of childlike dependence. We will all continue to live under the dictatorial control of the monster that we have created.<br>  
<I>Victoria Carter, vcarter@zoo.uvm.edu</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

Sir Winston Churchill stated, more than fifty years ago, "The women's suffrage movement is only the small edge of the wedge, if we allow women to vote it will mean the loss of social structure and the rise of every liberal cause under the sun." Now, some fifty years later, only Judge Robert Bork has had the courage to state, "Radical feminism is the most destructive and fanatical movement to come down to us from the Sixties. . . . Totalitarian in spirit, it is antagonistic to traditional Western culture and proposes the complete restructuring of society, morality, and human nature." And one of the major forces of that Radical Feminism, Catherine A. MacKinnon, has asserted that "feminism could supplant both Marxism and liberalism as a theory of politics." Should Congress put a rein on the courts? Indeed. But what is most needed is an emboldened male and female leadership that will have the courage of a Churchill and a Bork to tell the American public what it already knows, but quakes to acknowledgeEnd Feminism, restore America. The much derided, potatoe spelling champ Dan Quayle had a splendid moment when he challenged Murphy Brown, and that earned him years of scornful ridicule. Can it be possible that this mild-mannered ex-vice-president has evidenced more spine than the entire United States Congress?<br>  
<I>Jerry Rowles, jrowle19@ecity.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

Constitutionally, the courts only exist to interpret the law. The purpose of the federal courts and Supreme Court of the United States is only to decide the constitutionality of laws passed by the legislative body. In far too many instances, we find the court "creating law" by its ruling in issues. Precedents are set, and are interpreted as law by the populace. Technically, if a law is found to be unconstitutional, then it is up to the legislature to formulate a law that is constitutional regarding the issue at hand. Our nation has gone too long in permitting courts to "write law" by their rulings. Congress should place reins on the courts by re-writing laws that the court rules to be unconstitutional, especially when this is true on technical bases only. In addition, constitutionally, the Executive Branch of our government should only be the enforcer of laws passed by the legislature. It is Congress that represents the peoplenot the Courts, nor the President.<br>  
<I>Henry in Waco, TX</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>

U. S. Constitution Article III, Section 2: "In all cases affecting ambassadors, other public ministers and consuls, and those in which a state shall be a party, the Supreme Court shall have original jurisdiction. In all the other cases before-mentioned, the Supreme Court shall have appellate jurisdiction, both as to law and fact, with such exceptions, and under such regulations as the Congress shall make." I would like to recommend for your reading the Anti-Federalist Papers. The Anti-Federalist were written at the time when the Constitution was being formulated and its adoption considered. It critiqued of the Constitution and said much about the Judicial branch, which has come true.<br>  
<I>Jaime R. Purcell</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
The primary purpose of the federal judiciary is to protect our individual freedoms, and the rights of the people and the states, against encroachment by an oppressive central government. Sadly, the judges don't seem to do a very good job of it, but this is not the fault of our constitutionally mandated tripartite system; it is because the executive branch appoints lemons. If something needs to be reformed, it is the bloated and unresponsive executive branch of the Federal Government. We could begin by electing ethical presidents.<br>  
<I>Nick Chase, nick15@eve.assumption.edu</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/18/96<br>
Of course Congress should put a rein on the courts. Thomas "I love a good revolution" Jefferson put it well: "To consider judges as the ultimate arbiters of all constitutional questions [is] a very dangerous doctrine indeed, and one which would place us under the despotism of an oligarchy. Our judges are as honest as other men and not more so. They have, with others, the same passions for party, for power, and the privilege of their corps[a]nd their power is all the more dangerous as they are in office for life and not responsible . . .  to the elective control."<br> 
<I>Van Godbold, jericho@umich.edu</I> 
