<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
In the cases of 209, 187, welfare reform, yes, somehow we have to limit idiot judges in the Ninth District. Boy am I glad I moved from Taxifornia to South Dakota two years ago where unusual things are the Corn Palace and jackalopes at Wall Drug. I think I remember some folks leaving England for points west a while back over similar issues.<br> 
<I>Ken Russell, The Arlington Pottery, gone2pot@iw.net</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>

The people can control the courts by controlling for whom they vote. When conservative thought controls legislative bodies, those nominated for appointed offices and judgeships tend to be of the same mindset. The liberals do the same. Wise and thinking citizens not only vote, but cast their ballots for right-thinking people of unquestioned morals, both professionally and personally. This is for any election, from President to dogcatcher.<br> 
<I>Richard McKee, Dover, Delaware</I>
<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>

Yes Congress should rein in the Courts, although I am not sure how that would be accomplished. The Courts have too many times overturned the will of the people, and the will of the people reins supreme!<br> 
<I>Paul Oksnee, poksnee@netscape.com</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
The men who wrote the Constitution carefully designed a Federal Government with three separate and distinct parts, each part to act as a check against the other two. This implies an equal division of power among the three parts.<br> 
<I>Carl Conner, cconner@grove.net</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
Oh sure, reign in the courts now that they've passed a few decisions conservatives don't like. Last week, though, you were all just dying for an interventionist court to overturn the Brady Bill. Judges are committed to leaving their prejudices outside the courtroom, but nothing stops voters from carrying their bigotry into the voting booth. So Californians choose a strident repeal of the state's guarantee of civil rights, and Congress/puritanical legislatures forbid states from acknowledging the loving union of same-sex couples. The duty of the courts is to let democracy work, but keep it in check by screening out centuries-old hatreds (or sexist worldviews, such as those that deny women the right to control their own bodies). As such, an activist judiciary is crucial to a functioning democracyunless, of course, you think women and minorities don't count.<br>
<I>Leslie G. Burton</I>

<hr>
<P>
12/16/96<br>
Recent events suggest that the power is out of balance, having shifted toward the Judicial. This works to the advantage of the Executive which has the power of appointment. The legislative is weakened and with it the voice of the electorate. Two initiatives passed by the voters of California have been, in effect, nullified by federal judges. A majority of California's voters, its Governor and its legislature have been over ruled by one person who seemingly has the power of a dictator. At the very least the Congress should require that a federal judge explain in concrete rather than abstract 'read between the lines' detail exactly why he believes the law he over turned is unconstitutional. Lacking a rational reason, the judge should be overruled This last case is a real farce. The judge evidently believes that outlawing discrimination is unconstitutional! Great care must be taken to stop this type of nonsense without altering the system set up by the Founders. Restoration, not alteration, is what's needed here. I believe that we should not let Congress put a reign on the courts. The reason is simple . . . balance of power. Congress has a chance during a justice's appointment to approve a justice. Our Republican Congress should really scrutinize Clinton's appointments. Not just let them in without a hitch. Now it's too late to do anything. Maybe we should let the Citizens of the US put a reign on the courts? What do you think???<br> 
<I>RandyA8878@aol.com</I>
<hr>
<hr>
<P>

