<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Letter from John Breaux</title>
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">
<center><b><i><font size = +2>United States Senate</font></i></b>
<br>Washington, DC 20510-1803</center>
<p>
<center>March 24, 1995</center><p>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
Dear Colleague: <p>

As you well know, we in Congress have been deeply concerned about the very
low level of saving within the United States.  As a result, there have
been many bills introduced in this 104th Congress to increase personal
saving.  A number of Senators have cosponsored more than one. 

<p>

In addressing this vital need to increase household saving, and the
related tax revenue impact arising therefrom, it is important to recognize
a position that is widely accepted by economists:  the ordinary income tax
is biased against savings and favors consumption.  Thus, the only
remaining questions are:  how bad is the bias; how can we correct it; is
the government's tax revenue impacted; and what are the economic losses or
gains from change? 

<p>

This letter applies to a bill I have sponsored, S. 159.  This legislation
is unique in a number of ways, Most importantly, S. 159 totally removes
the income tax bias against personal saving in a simple, sound way.  My
legislation would permit unlimited tax deductible contributions to
Individual Investment Accounts (IIAs) by all taxpayers. 

<p>

Please review the enclosed summary of S. 159 and article by the Institute
for Research on the Economics of Taxation (IRET) which describes S. 159 as
&quot;...one of the boldest, most imaginative, and most constructive
pro-growth tax initiatives in many years.&quot; 

<p>

I hope that you will join me in this effort by cosponsoring S. 159. 
Please contact Geoff Culbertson (4-4623) for any additional information. 

                                      Sincerely, 


                                      JOHN BREAUX
                                      United States Senator

</pre>
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>], [<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>], 
Legislation Listed By: [<a href="/savers/legnum.html">Bill No.</a>] or [<a href="/savers/legname.html">Sponsor</a>]

</BODY>

