<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Conservative Spotlight - <i>HUMAN EVENTS</i> </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=2>September 13, 1996</FONT>  --  <i><b><FONT SIZE=2>HUMAN EVENTS</FONT></b></i><BR>
<P>
<table border=2 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=2>
<tr align=center>
<td>
<FONT SIZE=6>Conservative Spotlight</FONT><BR>
</tr>
<tr align=center>
<td>
By Steve Schwalm<BR>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5>Savers and Investors League</FONT><BR>
<P></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>GOP candidate Bob Dole's tax plan has put tax policy squarely at the forefront of the presidential debate this year, but as far as Tom Kelly is concerned, the plan doesn't go far enough.  Kelly, the ebullient founder and president of the Savers and Investor League (SIL), says that &quot;it is a step in the right direction,&quot; but complains that it &quot;doesn't touch the entire question of taxing savings.&quot;<BR>
<P>
&quot;Reducing the income tax on investment return by 15% is certainly an improvement, but is far short of the proper tax reduction of 100%,&quot; says Kelly.  After you have had your wage or salary income taxed once, he observes, &quot;whatever you have left can only be spent or saved.&quot;  If you save it, he argues, the government will continually tax it, penalizing and discouraging savings.  The result, he maintains, is that &quot;the American people are being ripped off.  People ask, 'Why aren't young people saving?'  Well, you don't have to be a rocket scientist to figure that one out.&quot;<BR>
<P>
According to Kelly, &quot;All of your savings and investments should be tax deductible and tax deferred.&quot;  Accumulating wealth in the form of either savings or investments, Kelly says, &quot;is the only way to become self-sufficient.  Penalizing savings takes away our self-sufficiency.&quot;<BR>
<P>
The Savers and Investors League lobbies Congress to change the antisavings bias of the tax code, while its affiliated Savers &amp; Investors Foundation carries out research on the impact of taxes on the American economy, taxpayers and government.  The mission of SIL, says Kelly, is to &quot;educate and motivate grassroots voters/taxpayers to challenge and change the way our government measures the tax revenue impact of tax-deferred savings.&quot;<BR>
<P>
A self-described &quot;entrepreneurial businessman,&quot; Kelly founded SIL in 1988 after a run-in with government destroyed his investment business.  &quot;This is not my vocation.  It's a labor of love, believe me.  I refuse to accept the notion that our government and our people can let this happen.&quot;<BR>
<P>
Kelly had been in business 15 years selling policyowner self-directed variable annuities when the IRS and Treasury Department obtained a court ruling overturning 70 previous rulings favorable to firms such as Kelly's and shut it down.  Kelly sued, and the U.S. District Court agreed with him, stating that the Treasury and IRS rulings were in fact arbitrary, capricious, illegal, and unreasonable and that the IRS had usurped the power of Congress.<BR>
<P>
In response to an IRS-Treasury petition, the U.S. Court of Appeals ruled, as technical matter and not on the substance of the suit, that the District Court did not have jurisdiction and overturned its decision.  Kelly hired Robert Bork, then a Yale Law School professor, to assist with his appeal to the Supreme Court, but, without stating its reasons, the Supreme Court refused to accept the case.  Thus, the Treasury and IRS won - but not on the merits of their tax law position - and Kelly was forced to liquidate his business in 1978.<BR>
<P>
This experience prompted Kelly to become an activist and after studying up on the matter, Kelly &quot;concluded that the way our nation taxes savings is absolutely, flat-out stupid.&quot;  The current mode of taxing, he argues, &quot;not only kills the accumulated capital and savings of individuals and collectively, our nation, it also kills the tax base of our government, and the government collects less taxes than they otherwise would...  Our nation has lost trillions and trillions of dollars of economic growth because of it.&quot;<BR>
<P>
Kelly does not fault legislators, who are not economists, for failing to understand the economics involved, but thinks that once tax policy got off track, precedent and habit kept it there.  He lays partial blame on accounting practices that began with the Budget Act of 1974, which basically assumes that all money somehow belongs to the government and that failure to tax any existing account, such as personal savings, is a government &quot;tax-expenditure.&quot;<BR>
<P>
As a result, says Kelly, government tax policy views allowing individuals to keep and save their own money as a subsidy.  &quotThis is 100% wrong!&quot; he says.<BR>
<P>
Observing that all the other major economic powers largely exempt savings and capital gains from taxation, Kelly sees his efforts beginning to bear fruit here as well.  SIL test mailings have shown tremendous popular support for the idea of tax-deferred savings, Kelly says, and &quot;we have a bill [H.R. 328 and S. 159] introduced, with very good sponsorship in Congress.  It's sponsored by John Breaux [D. - La.] in the Senate and Jim McCreary [R. - La.] in the House, and has a lot of support.  Dick Armey [R. - Tex.], who's an economist, is a cosponsor.&quot;<BR>
<P>
&quot;This whole taxation of savings question is right on the front burner,&quot; says Kelly, noting that all major tax proposals now include some form of totally tax-exempt savings, including The USA Tax Act (S. 722) sponsored by Senators Pete Domenici [R. - N.M.] and Sam Nunn [D. - Ga.].  &quot;I believe it's just like the Berlin Wall.  No one thought the Berlin Wall would ever come down, but because it was built on quicksand - poof! - the whole thing imploded, and the wall came down.  The same thing's going to happen with the way our nation taxes savings.&quot;<BR>
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>]<br>
