<HEAD>
<TITLE> Is a Balanced Budget the Key... </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<font size=2>Excerpts from the article of the same title have been reprinted here with permission from the<br>
</font><b>Durell Journal of Money and Banking, Spring 1996<br></b>
<p>
<hr>
<font size=6>Is a Balanced Budget the Key to<br>
Our Economic Future?<br>
</font>
<b>by CHARLES I. PLOSSER</b>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
I am probably not much different from most of you when I say that I listened - first with interest, then with laughter, and finally with complete dismay - to the verbal sparring among supposedly bright and able politicians during the recent budget debates.
<p>
<ul>
<li> Why must we be subjected to all the nonsensical and misleading posturing intended to gain support in the overnight opinion surveys by pitting one interest group against another?
<p>
<li> Why does the Secretary of the Treasury incite the fear of default on U.S. debt obligations when he knows fully well that there is no immediate threat?
<p>
<li> Why should members of Congress take the ludicrous stand that the budget must be balanced in seven years - not six, eight, or none, but seven and only seven years?
</ul>
...
<p>
If you could cut through all of the political grandstanding and use of the media to pander to specific interest groups, you would find, of course, claims that important philosophical issues are at stake.  These issues involve fundamental questions over the role and size of government and the structure of the tax system.  Indeed, that is where the real issues lie.
<p>
Unfortunately, these important questions are unlikely to be resolved or to dramatically change the way government affects the allocation of resources during the current Congress.  The very nature  of the legislative process, which entails compromise and a strong preference for the status quo, makes progress difficult and slow.  Instead, the Congress, Administration and policy gurus have, as a practical matter, chosen to make the budget deficit the focal point for the debate.
<p>
...
<p>
Attempting to reduce the deficit, of course, leads to a debate over the nature of the spending reductions and/or tax changes required to accomplish this goal.  The real danger of making deficit reduction the yardstick by which we measure the success of the budget process is that we may succeed in reducing the deficit, but not in resolving the more fundamental problems.
<p>
...
<p>
If I asked a group of Americans why they thought the budget deficit was a problem, I would get a variety of different answers.  But I think a common thread in their answers would be a concern over the health of our economy and the fear that our current high standard of living is likely to be at the expense of not just our own future, but that of our children and generations to come.
<p>
This is a real and justifiable concern.  But the fact is that even if we eliminate the budget deficit - however good that may make us feel - we will not necessarily deal a decisive blow to these more deeply rooted concerns.  In fact, eliminating the deficit is not even the most important step that the government can take towards addressing these concerns.  Much more important than the magnitude of the deficit - and whether it goes to zero in seven years, ten years or at all - is where and how the government spends the resources it takes from us and the nature of the incentives created by the way those revenues are raised.
<p>
If we wish to ensure the health and well-being of our future and that of our children, then we must increase the amount of savings and productive investments we undertake today so that we achieve continued growth of our standard of living.   Slow growth in domestic investment means slower growth in the amount of capital per worker.  This means slower growth in labor productivity and slower growth in real wages.  Make no mistake about it, growth is the key.  The difference between an economy that grows at 2 percent a year and one that grows at 3 percent a year becomes enormous due to compounding.  After 30 years the economy growing at 2 percent is about 80 percent wealthier while the economy growing at 3 percent is almost 150 percent wealthier.
<p>
I am troubled that too many people, in and out of government, are under the misguided impression that, as soon as we balance the budget, we can start congratulating ourselves for saving the nation from economic calamity and moral degradation.
<p>
You have no doubt heard or read that Americans don't save enough.  Among the major developed countries of the world, the U.S. has one of the lowest rates of gross saving.  For example, gross national saving as a percentage of GDP is 33 percent in Japan, 29 percent in Switzerland, 20 percent in Germany, 19 percent in France and only about 14 percent in the U.S.  This relatively low rate of saving means that any investment in productive capacity that exceeds our domestic savings must be supplied by foreigners.  Low domestic saving is the primary cause of our trade deficit - not the fact that some foreign markets are more closed to U.S. goods than we would like.
<p>
If we think of savings as the resource we choose to set aside for investment, then the investment rate represents that portion of output actually invested.  Here again, the U.S. has one of the lowest investment rates among the major industrial countries.  For example, gross fixed capital formation as a percentage of GPD is 31 percent in Japan, 23 percent in Germany, 21 percent in France, but only about 15 percent in the U.S.
<p>
...
<p>
...if we are not careful about how we shrink the deficit we could easily do so in a way that could actually make our low savings and investment patterns worse.  By increasing the tax on savings and investment and directing more government spending toward consumption or to entitlements for individuals with high rates of consumption, we could reduce the deficit but would actually further reduce the motivation to save and invest for the future.
<p>
As a matter of fact, our budget deficit is simply not that big relative to other countries, even countries that have substantially higher savings and investment rates.
<p>
...
<p>
If the deficit is the wrong focus for the debate, how should we think about addressing the real concerns about our economic future?  There are, of course, many factors that influence our individual decisions to save and invest.  It is important that Congress and the American people debate the impact of government spending decisions and tax policies, not simply in terms of their impact on the budget deficit, but in terms of their impact on investment and saving, and thus our ability to grow and enhance our standard of living.
<p>
Under the current patterns of spending and taxation, our government systematically biases individuals away from saving and investing and towards consumption.  This bias in the way the government spends our tax dollars and the way it raises those dollars is a significant contribution to the lower savings patterns that exist here relative to other industrialized nations.
<p>
...
<p>
Our current system which relies heavily on the income tax, is a system that taxes income that we use for consumer purchases only once, but taxes income that we save two and sometimes three times.  For example, under the income tax, wages, salaries, dividends, interest and capital gains are all taxed as personal income.  If we spend that money on a new car, there is no further income tax liability on the car or on the return or value we get from driving the car.
<p>
On the other hard, if we take those same after-tax dollars and save them or invest them in a business, then the return or the value received for those savings is taxed first at the level of the business and is then taxed again when the business distributes the profits back to the investors in the form of dividends or capital gains.  This system penalizes saving and investing and thus encourages consumption.  Since interest on debt is tax deductible to the business, this system also favors debt over equity as a means of financing business expansion.
<p>
For these reasons, economists have long argued in favor of some sort of consumption tax that would not have the same disincentives to save.  Under a consumption tax all savings would be exempt from tax until they were used to consume goods and services.  This approach is in sharp contrast to the current income tax, which penalizes future consumption by taxing it more heavily.
<p>
...
<p>
In the past, there has never been a strong political constituency for tax reform.  After all, as George Bernard Shaw once said, &quot;A government that robs Peter to pay Paul can always count on the support of Paul.&quot;  In this case, we are denying the benefits of our investments to future generations who, to my knowledge, have not yet found a lobbyist to represent their interests and thus seem to be easy prey for the government looking for someone to tax.
<p>
There is now an increasing awareness that fundamental tax reform is important if we are to come to grips with our low savings and under-investment problems.  We are coming to realize that deficit reduction alone is likely to result in a bitterly disappointing change in our savings patterns.
<p>
...
<p>
...we can rest assured that every group that believes they have a vested interest in specific provisions of the current tax code will argue strongly for preserving the status quo.  Who we won't hear from are those whose wages and living standards will be raised by the increase in capital a less distortionary tax code would promote.  These individuals are not nearly so organized - some of them haven't even been born.
<p>
We must come to grips with the concern that we are not investing enough to ensure real growth in capital and labor productivity that will enhance real wages and living standards in the future.  Additionally, we must also tackle the fundamental issue of tax reform.  If we reduce the deficit without reducing the double and triple taxation on savings and investment, we will have failed.  If the 1996 Presidential campaign does not make tax reform a defining issue, we will miss the greatest opportunity for fundamental tax reform since the 16th Amendment, which created the income tax 82 years ago.
<p>
There is little doubt in my mind that in the short run, the prospects for the economy are good.  The long run opportunities, however, are more troublesome.  We must move beyond the simple-minded and misguided forces on a balanced budget and come to grips with the underlying weakness in our savings and investment patterns that threatens the standard of living of our children.  The current debates in Washington have opened a small crack in the door of the entrenched interests of the bureaucracy that invites a serious discussion of these fundamental concerns.  Combine this with the fact that 1996 is a presidential election year and we have perhaps a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to make fundamental tax reform a major political issue.  The political risks will be high, but so could the economic rewards to the nation.  It should make for a very interesting 1996.
<p>
<hr>
<i><center>Charles I. Plosser is Dean and John M. Olin Distinguished Professor of<br>
Economics and Public Policy, William E. Simon Graduate School of Business<br>
Administration, University of Rochester.
</i>
<hr>
<p><font size=2>
Copies of the full text of this article are available from: <br>
The Durell Institute at Shenandoah University<br>
1460 University Drive, Winchester, VA  22601<br>
Phone: 1-800-887-9920 <br>  E-mail: durell@su.edu
<br></font>
<p></center>
