<html>
<head>
<title>Job Prospects for College Graduates</title>
</head>

<body background="/yaf/ground2.gif">

<center>
<img alt="Employment Services" src="em-logo.gif"><p>
</center>
<p>

<i>	College students, don't despair!  Though the job market is tight, Young America's Foundation can give you a leg up on your competition.  Through our jobs program, Job Prospects for College Graduates, you will know what employers are looking for.  Bring a corporate leader to your school who will tell you what you need to do in college to get a good job when you graduate.  And he will tell you about the realities of the job market.  In addition, a free market economist will tell you about the benefits of the free market system. . . a perspective you won't find often on campuses!<p>
</i>
	College students are wise to be particularly concerned this year about finding a job after graduation.  Studies show that as of graduation day, only 40 percent of the class of 1995 had found a job appropriate for their degree.  That number goes up only to 50 percent by November.  To make matters worse, studies show that employers are losing faith in the ability of colleges to prepare students for the workforce.  They are looking more at the experience of a potential employee rather than their academic record.<p>

	What is the reason for these phenomena?  There are two explanations.  First, the quality of our colleges and universities are eroding.  Except at a few select schools which have maintained their commitment to academic instruction, multicultural and politically correct courses supplant classes with practical value for future employment.  And second, the Clinton Administration's regulatory policies are forcing businesses to forgo expansion.  When employers must hire, they opt for trained, experienced individuals, rather than taking a chance on a new graduate.  Government regulations make the expense and hassle of bringing on even an experienced worker prohibitive.  Why, then, would an employer opt to hire someone fresh out of college, with no experience, and very likely in need of remedial education, in addition to basic job training?<p>

	Do not despair!  Young America's Foundation has a program which will help students maximize their college degree so that employers will snatch them up, or at least give them a chance.  In addition, students will learn the real reasons why it is so tough to get a job for which befits their degree.<p>

<i>	Job Prospects for College Graduates</i> is a program designed to promote an accurate understanding of our free market system of economics.  We seek to dispel the widespread myth, promoted by leftist professors, that "big business" is responsible for the difficulty recent college graduates encounter when they attempt to enter the work force.  Specifically, we are examining the impact of burdensome federal regulations and of the federal government itself in constraining the job market.  In addition, we are focusing on the devaluation of today's college degree given the politicized curricula, and the consequent skepticism of employers of higher education's ability to prepare students for the workplace.<p>

	During the fall of 1995, Young America's Foundation will cosponsor a series of<i> Job Prospects for College Graduates</i> programs on campuses.  At each program, a free market economist and a corporate leader will speak to students giving them the insights they need to maximize their educational opportunities and avoid the pitfalls of a politically correct degree.  In addition, students will gain a unique understanding of their job opportunities and of the qualities employers are seeking in new recruits.<p>

	Young America's Foundation is publishing a monograph written by Dr. Thomas J. DiLorenzo for the Foundation entitled,<i> Job Prospects for College Graduates:  The Role of Government and The Responsibilities of the University.</i>  The monograph will be available to all students.<p>

	If you are interested in hosting Job Prospects for College Graduates at your campus, please contact <a href="mailto:yaf@yaf.org">Steve Slivinski</a> (yaf@yaf.org) at Young America's Foundation: 1-800-292-9231.<p><p>

[ <a href="home.html">Home</a> ]<p><p>

</body>
</html>
